com.facebook.buck.rules

Class DoNotUseAbstractBuildable

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.facebook.buck.rules.AbstractCachingBuildRule
      • com.facebook.buck.rules.DoNotUseAbstractBuildable
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Buildable, BuildRule, Comparable<BuildRule>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AndroidBinaryRule, AndroidResourceRule, DefaultJavaLibraryRule, Genrule, JavaBinaryRule, PrebuiltJarRule, PythonBinaryRule, ShBinaryRule, ShTestRule

    public abstract class DoNotUseAbstractBuildable
extends AbstractCachingBuildRule
implements Buildable
    No-op implementations of all methods from Buildable. To switch to AbstractBuildable:
    1. Change the class the rule extends.
    2. Modifying its Builder to extend AbstractBuildable.Builder (this is important!)
    3. Fix compilation errors
    4. Check for usages in the buck code base (particularly instanceof checks and casts)
    5. ...
    6. profit

      • getEnhancedDeps

        @Nullable
public ImmutableSortedSet<BuildRule> getEnhancedDeps(BuildRuleResolver ruleResolver)
        Description copied from interface: Buildable
        A Buildable may employ graph enhancement to alter its dependencies. If it does this, it must return the new dependencies via this method.
        Specified by:
        getEnhancedDeps in interface Buildable
        Parameters:
        ruleResolver - that can be used to get the BuildRule that corresponds to a BuildTarget if the rule for the target has already been constructed.
        Returns:
        The deps for the BuildRule that contains this Buildable. These may differ from the deps specified in the original build file due to graph enhancement. If the deps are unchanged, then this method should return null.

      • getDeps

        public final ImmutableSortedSet<BuildRule> getDeps()
        Specified by:
        getDeps in interface BuildRule
        Returns:
        the set of rules that must be built before this rule. Normally, this matches the value of the deps argument for this build rule in the build file in which it was defined.

        However, there are special cases where other arguments pull in implicit dependencies (e.g., the keystore argument in android_binary). In these cases, the implicit dependencies are also included in the set returned by this method. The value of the original deps argument, as defined in the build file, must be accessed via a custom getter provided by the build rule.
